<div id="review_3273915874" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3273915874" />
    <a title="Cooper Ackerly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/103383457-cooper-ackerly"><img alt="Cooper Ackerly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621955127p2/103383457.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3273915874?book_show_action=true">Sep 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cooper Ackerly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cooper Ackerly" href="/user/show/103383457-cooper-ackerly">Cooper Ackerly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140440751" href="/book/show/103390.The_Song_of_Roland">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3273915874" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2475680109344524839">There are, perhaps, few things more revealing about The Song of Roland than the fact that the original story behind the legend consisted of a slaughter of Charlemange&apos;s army by a group of marauding Basques. <br/><br/>It goes without saying that I found the superficial content of the poem to be absolutely reprehensible. Its author displays a knowledge of Islamic culture and religion on par with that of a Fox news anchor, and there&apos;s a not-so-subtle undercurrent of jealousy as well. The sole redeeming chara</span>
  <span id="freeText2475680109344524839" style="display:none">There are, perhaps, few things more revealing about The Song of Roland than the fact that the original story behind the legend consisted of a slaughter of Charlemange's army by a group of marauding Basques. <br /><br />It goes without saying that I found the superficial content of the poem to be absolutely reprehensible. Its author displays a knowledge of Islamic culture and religion on par with that of a Fox news anchor, and there's a not-so-subtle undercurrent of jealousy as well. The sole redeeming characteristic of (some of) the Saracen soldiers is that of bravery, presumably because the French soldiers would lack any claim to valiance had their enemies been as physically corrupt as the French thought they were morally. <br /><br />Yet The Song of Roland is absolutely fascinating anthropologically speaking. Its original purpose aside, it seems to be an extended proof of the Shakesperean maxim that the Devil quotes Scripture. I recommend it in conjunction with Bertrand Russell's "Why I Am Not a Christian" and "Has Religion Made Useful Contributions to Civilization?," as the three together make quite a compelling case.<br /><br />Oh, and Sayers' translation is absolutely gorgeous. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2475680109344524839" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

