    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_997989909" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/997989909" />
    <a title="Charles Dee Mitchell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2272557-charles-dee-mitchell"><img alt="Charles Dee Mitchell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1267455462p2/2272557.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/997989909?book_show_action=true">Jul 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Charles Dee Mitchell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Charles Dee Mitchell" href="/user/show/2272557-charles-dee-mitchell">Charles Dee Mitchell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140440751" href="/book/show/103390.The_Song_of_Roland">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2272557-charles-dee-mitchell?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2272557-charles-dee-mitchell?shelf=medieval">medieval</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer997989909" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10014411987745887184">As other reader reviews make plain, this medieval celebration of holy war proves problematic for modern readers.<br/><br/>It&apos;s the late 8th century, and Charlemagne has spent a busy seven years clearing Spain of infidels. The campaign has been a success, but the stronghold of Saragossa remains under Muslim rule. Charlemagne, ready to go home, works a deal with King Marsile for a heavy pay off, but the deal is brokered by the traitor Ganelon. He arranges for Charlemagne&apos;s rearguard that is transporting all</span>
  <span id="freeText10014411987745887184" style="display:none">As other reader reviews make plain, this medieval celebration of holy war proves problematic for modern readers.<br /><br />It's the late 8th century, and Charlemagne has spent a busy seven years clearing Spain of infidels. The campaign has been a success, but the stronghold of Saragossa remains under Muslim rule. Charlemagne, ready to go home, works a deal with King Marsile for a heavy pay off, but the deal is brokered by the traitor Ganelon. He arranges for Charlemagne's rearguard that is transporting all the booty to be ambushed by Marsile's Saracen army. His motivation is largely to arrange the death of Charlemagne's nephew, Count Roland, a young man who insulted Ganelon at a meeting of the peerage. (These are very touchy people.) The Battle of Roncevaux ensues.<br /><br />Vilifying the enemy is standard procedure in war propaganda, and the anonymous composers of this <i>chanson</i> are enthusiastic pros. All the Frankish peers are incomparably noble, strong, and brave. Although they will be massacred by the Saracens, they first do an excellent job of eviscerating the enemy. Crushing blows send brains oozing from ears. Swords and spears spill guts onto the ground. What initially seems like a realistic picture of medieval carnage soon gives way to the fantastic. Single blows halve Saracen bodes from the crown of the head through to pelvis before splitting the spine of the opponent's hapless mount. Franks are hacked to pieces as well, but the true heros of the battle have remarkable stamina. A bellicose archbishop receives fatal wounds yet manages to kill an additional 400 Saracens before dying. <br /><br />That archbishop is quite a character. He blesses the troops and encourages the martyrs with the knowledge that seconds after their deaths they will find themselves in Paradise. As the Saracens die, he is pleased to know that devils have dragged their souls to Hell. <br /><br />Although the royalty among the Saracens are nobly presented, their rank and file are made up of grotesque peoples lacking any sense of decency. My favorites were the giants with bristly hair on the spines like pigs, and one group whose iron-hard skin precludes the need of armor. The poem's authors also have either peculiar notions or absolutely no regard for Islam. Repeatedly we are told that the Saracens worship Mohammed, Apollo, and some other god I had never heard of. They also build idols to these gods. I guess all those idols of Mohammed have made their way into the dustbin of history. <br /><br />If this is a foundational text of Western Civilization, it is not one to be particularly proud of. <i>The Song of Roland</i> is a work of its period, and readers must make the effort to enter the world view it describes. That doesn't mean modern readers need to find its militant view of Christianity anything admirable. After the massacre at Roncevaux, Charlemagne's main forces arrive and take Saragossa. Among the Saracen prisoners, 100,000 accept Christ, are baptized, and their souls are saved. A recalcitrant 30,000 or so refuse and face beheading, hanging, or burning. Of course had the battle gone the other way, Frankish captives would have faced a similar decision. <br /><br />When Charlemagne makes it home to Aix, the angel Gabriel, who puts in an appearance at various crucial moments of the narrative, informs the aging monarch that he has further wars to fight. "God", says the king, "how wearisome my life it."<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10014411987745887184" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

