    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_49885086" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/49885086" />
    <a title="Tim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/978026-tim"><img alt="Tim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1251925098p2/978026.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/49885086?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tim" href="/user/show/978026-tim">Tim</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140445329" href="/book/show/763841.The_Song_of_Roland">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer49885086" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2798969907587787948">The Song of Roland, while about Charlemagne (800 AD) , is really a story of the Crusading era (ca. 1100 AD). Einhard, Charlemagne&apos;s biographer, notes in passing that the battle of Roncesvalles was fought against Basques, but in the Song, the enemy is the Saracen. And while some of the Saracens are depicted as evil, and many die being cleaved from head down to the spine of the horse they are riding, the real evils of this story are the treacherous Ganelon and Roland&apos;s own pride. Unwilling to blow</span>
  <span id="freeText2798969907587787948" style="display:none">The Song of Roland, while about Charlemagne (800 AD) , is really a story of the Crusading era (ca. 1100 AD). Einhard, Charlemagne's biographer, notes in passing that the battle of Roncesvalles was fought against Basques, but in the Song, the enemy is the Saracen. And while some of the Saracens are depicted as evil, and many die being cleaved from head down to the spine of the horse they are riding, the real evils of this story are the treacherous Ganelon and Roland's own pride. Unwilling to blow his horn and call for aid when the rearguard he commands is ambushed, Roland and his valiant men die for the sake of honor. It is admired, but is also clearly seen as unnecessary. A vivid translation. <br /><br />	I love the criticism of the medieval mindset that cannot "understand" the Islamic "other". At least some of the Saracens were noted to be noble knights, a much better understanding than American depictions of the German "Huns" during WWI or the crazed and savage "Japs" during WWII. Humans find it much easier to demonize their enemies, then to understand them. It makes it so much easier to kill them. Let us say post-enlightenment nation states have been much better at such demonization than medieval poems ever could be. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2798969907587787948" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


